SurveyData

An in-class survey was given to 362 introductory statistics students over several years. The StudentSurvey data contains 17 variables recorded for each student. They are as follows:

Year: Year in school: FirstYear, Sophomore, Junior, or Senior

Gender: M or F

Smoke: “No” or “Yes”

Award: Preferred award: Academy, Nobel or Olympic

HigherSAT: Which SAT score was higher: Math or Verbal

Exercise: Hours of exercise per week

TV: Hours of TV viewing per week

Height: Height in inches

Weight: Weight in pounds

Siblings: Number of Siblings

BirthOrder: Birth order: 1=oldest, 2=second oldest, etc.

VerbalSAT: Verbal SAT score

MathSAT: Math SAT score

SAT: Combined Verbal + Math SAT

GPA: College GPA

Pulse: Pulse Rate (beats per minute)

Piercings: Number of body piercings

The StudentSurvey data can be downloaded from the folder for homework 2 on Blackboard. Put this data set in your folder for homework 2.

To read these data into your R Console:

  1. In the menu for RStudio above, select Tools->Import Dataset->From Text File… (depending on the version of RStudio you are using, you may need to select File->Import Dataset->From CSV…).

  2. Navigate to the correct file in your folder for homework 2.

  3. Click on the StudentSurvey file and choose Open.

  4. A window will pop up where you can preview the data set and possibly choose different options for downloading this data. For this data set, the defaults are appropriate. Click once on Import to read the data into the R Console.

You now should see this data listed in the “Environment” window in the upper right corner of RStudio.

Problem 2

One of the questions asked on the StudentSurvey was, “Which award would you prefer to win: an Academy Award, a Nobel Prize, or an Olympic gold medal?”

  1. Which award was most popular amongst students? Create a table of counts for Award with R’s table() function.
t = table(SS$Award)
print(t)
##

##      31     149     182
paste0("The most popular award is ", names(which(t == max(t))))
## [1] "The most popular award is Olympic"
  1. Was the proportion of students preferring each award different for women and men? Explain. Complete the following steps to answer this question.
    1. Create a relative frequency bar chart for Award by Gender. The proportions of the preferred awards for each gender should sum to 1. You may get the necessary counts using the table() function in R, but it may take more than 1 step. Do all calculations necessary in the code chunk.
    2. Title this chart “Award by Gender”
    3. The bars for Males and Females should be side by side
    4. Include a legend for gender using “F” and “M” as the labels
    5. Make the bars vertical
    6. Set ylim=c(0, 0.6)
      1. Include the option, args.legend = list(x="topleft")
      2. Don’t forget to answer the question!
barplot(prop.table(table(SS$Gender,SS$Award)),
        main = "Award by Gender",
        legend.text = c(levels(SS$Gender)),
        ylim = c(0,0.6),
        args.legend = list(x="topleft"),
        col=c("orange","blue"),
        xlab = "Award Type",
        ylab = "Probability",
        beside = T
)

The proportions for each award were different for men and women. Women preferred Academy awards more than men, and men preferred Olympic medals more than women. Men and women preferred Nobel prizes at about the same rate.

I would describe the distribution as unimodal with a left skew

The range of exercise is 0 - 40. A student exercising more than half of sample would have to be exercising at least 10 hrs/week since the data is a discrete integer.

Those who aspire for an Olympic medal on average exercise more than those who aspire to a Nobel prize or an academy award.

Problem 5

Is there a relationship between the number of hours of TV you watch and your GPA?

  1. Create a scatterplot of GPA by TV using the code below.
plot(SS$TV, SS$GPA)

  1. Does there appear to be a relationship between the number of hours watching TV and college GPA?

There seems to be a compression in the variation of scores as TV watching increases but the mean GPA appears to remain the same, i.e. the line of best fit has a slope of 0.

  1. Let’s take a look at this relationship again after excluding students who watch 40 hours of TV a week or more. Do this in two lines. First, create a new data frame (using the subset function). Second, use plot.
# First line: create new data frame that keeps only students with TV under 40  
ss.lessthan40 = subset(SS,TV<40)
# Second line: call plot function with this newly created data frame
plot(ss.lessthan40$TV,ss.lessthan40$GPA)

  1. We can look at the difference in this relationship between males and females by coloring the female observation red. Is this relationship any different for females compared to males? You will do this in three lines of code. In the first line, simply repeat the previous call to plot that you wrote in part c; in the second line, create a data frame called females that only has the rows corresponding to women; the third line is written for you.
# First line: Call to plot function from second line of part c
plot(ss.lessthan40$TV,ss.lessthan40$GPA)
# Second line: create data frame called females
ss.females = subset(SS,Gender=="F")
points(ss.females$TV, ss.females$GPA, col='red') # this is third line

There does not seem to be a difference in the the effect of TV watching on college GPA between males and females.

  1. What was the effect of the points() function above? > points() draws points at specified coordinates and the argument col = "red" colors them red.
